Traditionally, parts of our code base that are run in node are compiled into CommonJS.
This makes sense, since CommonJS was made for Node.

However, modern frontend frameworks like Vite and even NextJS vastly prefer to work with ESM.
They might have to take additional time transpiling your built code from CJS to ESM.
So, for libraries that are shared between node and the browser,
it would be good to build them into ESM in the first place.

However, switching the build to ESM means you're now subjected to Node's new limitations.

Typescript never modifies your import specifiers, so what can we do?
Fortunately, I've found this handy tool: tsc-esm-fix.
It can fix your source code to comply with Node's new restrictions.

To see the working CommonJS version:

```
./build
./run
```

To run up against node's rescriptions:

- change package.json's type to "module"
- change tsconfig.json's module to ESNext (or NodeNext - tsc-esm-fix will print an error, but you can ignore it)

```
./build
./run
```

To fix the source code:

```
./fix
./build
./run
```
